Introduction

  • The U.S. Small Business Administration (SBA) helps small businesses and entrepreneurs achieve the american dream by its estimation.
  • It was created in 1953 and is a cabinet level agency that provides counselling capital and contracting expertise to small business.
  • It is the U.S. only go-to for resources and advocacy for small bussiness.
  • Its mission statement stated plainly on its webpage is to helps Americans start, grow, and build resilient businesses.
  • A data set comprising businesses just like that was explored here, where sampling methods were employed. Some recommendations regarding those methods may follow.

Data Set Description

  • The name of the data set is National SBA (Small Business Administration).
  • It is described as census type data.
  • It was contained in 9 csv files eight of which held 100,000 observations each, with the ninth holding 99164 observations.
  • The data sets were combined into one data set called loan, with 899,164 observations total. There are 28 variables in loan. t
  • The source of the data set is expressed to be from the United States Small Business Administration.
    • A description of the data set, taken from its origin, states that this data set isprovides historical data from 1987 through 2014[for loans]that was guaranteed to some degree by the SBA.
  • Included is a variable [MIS_Status] which indicates if the loan was paid in full or defaulted/charged off. Below should be a printout of the structure of the data set.

Stratification (1/3)

  • According to the North American Industry Classification System, (NAICS) is the standard used by Federal statistical agencies in classifying business establishments for the purpose of collecting, analyzing, and publishing statistical data related to the U.S. business economy.
  • Below is a proportion/frequency table for the North America Industry Classification System (NAICS) Codes.
  • Above that table is table of some the values for the NAICS variable.
    • It may be clear that these values vary from one another.
    • However, the system codifies them by their first two digits.
    • The proportion/frequency table holds proportions and frequencies of those codes after the values within the NAICS variable were combined with the NAICS codification.
  • These NAICS codes were used to stratify the data set.
  • Those subsets were then sampled from.

Stratified Sample

  • Here stratified sampling was conducted.
  • The data set should of had a samples for each category taken at 10%.
  • Each of the Industries were subset on the variable UrbanRural.
    • its values were expressed to be 0 = undefined, 1 = urban, and 2 = rural.
    • The variable was not given a description outside of that.
    • It was believed that these designations refer to where the business that received these loans is located.
    • One might imagine then that some industries are represented in some settings better than others.
  • Some tables follow.
    • There are seven columns.
    • The first should show the Industry codes.
    • The next should show the UrbanRural status and default status, then the amount of those statuses within the sample.
    • The industry level samples should follow under Totals.
    • Then the samples default rate and industrys default rates should round out the far right.
  • One may note that there are entries missing in the first and last table.
    • Inspecting the Sample Default Rates table for SRAT0, entries for 55 and 92 are missing and in the Industry Default Rates table for SRAT0 55 is missing.
    • Like wise one may notice that in the Sample Default Rates table for SRAT2 that entries for 55 are missing.

Discussion (1/3)

  • Sampling was conducted on the a bank loan data set.
    • Three types were explored
      • Simple Random Sampling,
      • Systematic SRS
      • Stratified SRS
  • The data set had the all missing values within the default status variable removed.
  • Then it should have been stratified along indusrty lines.
    • Industry codifications using the NAICS were employed here.
    • There were 21 industries in all.
    • within those industries sampling was conducted.
  • For the stratified process, the industries were subset on the UrbanRural variable.
    • From there, default rates were calculated from those sample.
  • Lastly tables that may allow one to compare the samples default rate to the industrys default rate were presented.
    • Sample sizes were take at 10% for each of the procedures.
    • Factors like the size of each subset and naivete may be among the reasons for this.
  • After the tables were constructed, visualization of that information were presented, too.

Discussion (2/3)

  • From the tables and visualizations it may be clear that the SRS and SYS sampling had default rates close to the population default rates.
  • However, it seems across the board the SRS seemed to be closer in in almost every industry.
  • From the tables for the Stratified procedures in alomost every industry along every UrbanRural level the samples default rate was higher than industrys default rate.
  • These results may warrant further study.
  • Cluster sampling was not undertaken.
    • Difficulties involving time, understanding, certainty, and other factors, may be sited for that.

Discussion (3/3)

  • Inspecting the Sample Default Rates table for SRAT0 one may notice that entries for 55 and 92 are missing and in the Industry Default Rates table for SRAT0 55 is missing.
  • Like wise one may notice that in the Sample Default Rates table for SRAT2 that entries for 55 are missing.
  • One may blame the proportions of the values in the dataset for this.

Conclusion

In conclusion, there is not enough information to provide a recommendation for these sampling methods. Future work may include sample size tweeks, further exploration of criteria to create a cluster variable, and understanding the discrepencies in the stratified procedure.
